  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Mandates reporting of suspicious activity\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering\n\n3. The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988\n- Enhanced money laundering penalties\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n\n4. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Strengthened anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased information sharing between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\n5. The Currency and Foreign Transactions Reporting Act\n- Requires reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n- Helps track potential money laundering activities\n\nAt the state level, many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws. These laws typically define money laundering as the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems.\n\nFederal agencies like the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) and the Department of Justice are primarily responsible for investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses.",
